“Nick” should not be averse to criticism, and must desist from unwarranted harassment of the media, as this will certainly be his downfall.
He should listen more and talk less, for the good of the game. After all, there have been many federation presidents before him, and many more will come after, for there's no individual bigger than the beautiful game of association football.
Not even Fifa President Gianni Infantino.
Often, Kenyan media is roundly condemned for focusing too much on the English Premier League and other well-organised competitions like the Uefa Champions League.
But with such treatment visited on local scribes by an arrogant federation, who would bother risking a limb to cover domestic competition?
Our matter is currently in the hands of the Media Council of Kenya who will advise on the way forward. In the interim, the blackout on all FKF leagues and activities remains in full force.
Meanwhile, I can’t wait for competitions that show respect for media to kick off... Like the annual Koth Biro Cup that lights up Ziwani every year.  
Here, we don’t risk intimidation by FKF police!  



